<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-194-202  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 194 202.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Magazine  March 27 1990 v9 n6 p44(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>BackLoader 2 automates LaserJet font handling. (Software Review)(Roxxolid Corp.'s font management software) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mendelson, Edward.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Roxxolid Corp's $89 BackLoader 2 allows a user to eliminate theneed to write batch files or macros in downloading files.andP;  Theprogram keeps track of the fonts it downloads and will thereforenot download the same font twice.andP;  When used with MicrosoftWindows and other applications that download soft fonts with eachprint job, BackLoader 2 saves time.andP;  The product works with the HPLaserJet, DeskJet and other compatible printers.andP;  BackLoader'sautomatic downloads are transparent, but the user will not noticethe difference until he sees the results on paper.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Roxxolid Corp. (products).andO;Product:   HP LaserJet (Computer printer) (computer programs)Backloader 2 (Utility program).andO;Topic:     EvaluationFontsUtility Programs.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Load a copy of Roxxolid Corp.'s $89 BackLoader 2 into your computer's memory,and you'll never have to think about whether your soft fonts are in yourLaserJet or DeskJet's memory.andM;While BackLoader 2 lurks in RAM as a TSR, it waits for an application to sendthe printer a command to start using a soft font.andP;  When such a commandappears, BackLoader interrupts and downloads die font so that the fontreaches the printer before the command does.andP;  You can tell your applicationsthat the fonts are permanently resident in die printer, just like cartridgefonts, and you can forget about writing batch files or macros to downloadfonts for you.andM;Because Backloader keeps track of die fonts it downloads, it won't waste timedownloading the same font twice.andP;  With Microsoft Windows and otherapplications that normally download soft fonts with each print job, the timesavings can be noticeable.andM;Most LaserJets have limited internal memory for fonts or can't handle morethan 32 fonts at once.andP;  When BackLoader detects that you're about to reachthe limit, it tens the printer to clear the least recently used font from itsmemory and substitutes the one you need now.andM;When BackLoader 2 was first released, it occupied 29K of DOS memory-or 21K ifyou loaded a version that used a pop-up status line in place of a full pop-upmenu.andP;  A new version will use expanded memory to reduce the bite taken out ofmemory to less than 10K.andM;In addition to its on-the-fly font fielding, BackLoader supports all standarddownload functions.andP;  It can send a predefine set of fonts to the printer whenyou start a session or let you select individual fonts to download from apop-up screen.andP;  With applications that don't support soft fonts, you caninsert two-letter control codes that BackLoader translates into commands touse soft fonts.andM;Most of these other functions are implemented awkwardly and useless-than-straightforward syntax.andP;  ButandM;BackLoader's automatic downloads are so transparent that you'll scarcelyrealize they're happening until you see the results on paper.andO;</TEXT></DOC>